<br>
Learn it, live it.<br>
<br>
Too many simpletons expect someone else to pay for their mistakes.  All accidents can be prevented, acts of god/nature can't and yes Virginia there is a difference. (E.g.. spilling coffee on keyboard = accident / Tornado wiping out local trailer park = act of god/nature) <br>
<br>
I think it is not the responsibility of government to place regulations that are unnecessary or redundant.  Or for that matter allow for imbeciles to waste time and money filing what to me are frivolous lawsuits.  The woman the burnt herself with coffee v. McDonalds is just one example of stupidity married to litigiousness gone wrong.  Everyone knows coffee is hot, you ever try and take a sip of coffee fresh from the maker? damn hot stuff, don't matter if it is 135 or 185 degrees, you are still going to burn your tongue.  Is why most of us have the presence of mind to wait till it has cooled to drink from it and damn sure are going to be as cautious as we can to not spill it on ourselves or anything else for that matter.  Now if an employee had thrown it at her or spilled it on her then I could see a lawsuit being brought for maliciousness or negligence.  That was not the case, woman drove up and ordered and received the coffee and then spilled it on herself.  Who is to blame?  Her I think in that case.<br>
<br>
As for holding parent responsible for the actions of their kids, I am of two minds on that.  Firstly I do think that parents should be held responsible for their children's actions when it could endanger the lives and welfare of others. For example minor children that are allowed to use the family car, or are allowed access to fire arms.  If the child uses either of those in a fashion that places people or themselves at risk then yes I think the parents do bear responsibility because they should control the child's ability to use them.  By allowing the child to use such an item the parent is in effect saying "I trust my child's judgement and ability to use <item>".  In the case of motor vehicles the parents are already taking on added responsibilities in the form of increased insurance rates etc. so no new legislation is warranted.  Fire arms are another matter entirely, no insurance that covers "accidents" is widely available.  Therefore some form of legislation would seem to be warranted to hold the guardians legally and financially responsible for the actions of their minor children when those actions involve fire arms.  (Sidenote: if you have guns and kids, invest in a gunsafe and keep your fire arms locked up and unloaded at all times.  Personal defense weapons can be equipped with trigger locks etc.  Also get ahold of your local gun club or NRA rep and enroll yourself and kids in gun safety and awareness classes.)<br>
 <br>
As for fining parents because little Tommy didn't wear a helmet while out on his first 2-wheeler......what a load of @#%$.<br>
Yes bicycle helmets save lives, my brother was in an accident involving him on his mountain bike and a teen in driving a car, she said she didn't see him.  He went flying a good 15 feet when she hit him while she was supposedly doing the posted speed limit of 25 MPH.....yeah right sugar tell me another one.<br>
I digress.  The fact he was wearing the proper head gear saved his noggin, it collapsed and absorbed the impact as designed and all he received was a bad case of road rash and some bruises.  Parents and children alike need to be educated on the benefits of helmet and other protective item usage.  <br>
<br>
Many community police departments sponsor annual 'Bike rodeos' and the like to show the public safe habits and practices for cycling.  It would be of great benefit for parents to involve their children in activities like that as well as searching out other information sources.<br>
<br>
Fining the parent for the child's lack of helmet use is ludicrous.  The law sounds like a sad excuse of some local official to look like he/she cares about the safety of children. All it would seem to do is take cash out of the parents pocket and put it in the local gov't's pocket.  There are far to many other laws the officer could have been out enforcing.  A ticket not only takes time to write, the officer must also fill out an report, file the report and in most places a court date is set taking up time in our already over taxed judicial system.<br>
A huge waste of time? Absolutely, I doubt the 30$ or so would even cover the cost of the wages paid to the officer for the time it takes him to write everything up etc. and I know it wouldn't even begin to cover the time spent on it by the various court employees involved.  Less expensive way to get the kid to wear his/her helmet is to teach them why they need to wear it rather than make a law and waste time enforcing it.  <br>
<br>
